about his sexuality.

36:05.033 --> 36:09.267 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I wonder if you have a
sense of why he wanted
to keep that to himself.

36:09.267 --> 36:14.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TIM TEEMAN: I think, sometimes,
especially now, with the
acceleration of cultural change

36:16.233 --> 36:20.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and acceptance, as it's known,
I think we sometimes forget
what those times were like

36:22.167 --> 36:25.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
back in the '80s and even
into the '90s, before he was
forced out of the closet.

36:25.033 --> 36:30.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These were not times of large
numbers of celebrities of any
kind out of the closet at all.

36:32.000 --> 36:35.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You might remember, in the
very late '90s, Ellen's coming
out over here was a big, big

36:35.333 --> 36:37.300 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
cultural moment.

36:37.300 --> 36:41.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so I sometimes think we
forget how, in those days,
coming out of the closet, if you

36:43.733 --> 36:46.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
were famous, and, in fact,
coming out of the closet if you
were anybody was a very brave,

36:46.367 --> 36:48.900 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
wonderful act.

36:48.900 --> 36:51.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Harvey Milk, the wonderful
Harvey Milk, had it
exactly right when he
said the most important

36:51.267 --> 36:55.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and wonderful thing an LGBT
person could do was come out.

36:55.000 --> 36:57.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It was the most powerful
statement they could make.

36:57.133 --> 37:01.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the interesting thing about
George Michael is that, yes,
he kept it quiet, though it

37:01.300 --> 37:06.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
always -- I remember growing
up in the era of tabloid bait
and insinuation around stars

37:07.467 --> 37:09.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
like George Michael
and his sexuality.

37:09.333 --> 37:10.967 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He did play equality concerts.

37:10.967 --> 37:14.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
He donated and sang at
HIV and AIDS benefits.

37:14.900 --> 37:17.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
While he was in the closet, he
fell in love for the first time.

37:17.433 --> 37:22.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And his first lover died
in 1993 of an AIDS-related
brain hemorrhage.

37:24.400 --> 37:27.467 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So he had a gay life,
and he was coming to
terms with something
himself in that period.

37:28.933 --> 37:31.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And he talked later on about the
complexity of his own sexuality.

37:31.900 --> 37:33.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Maybe he wasn't ready.

37:33.100 --> 37:35.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Maybe there were
commercial concerns.

37:35.133 --> 37:39.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But then, in 1998, as you say,
and as Angus Walker said in his
report that you just played,

37:39.100 --> 37:41.567 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
came this arrest in Los Angeles.

37:41.567 --> 37:45.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And George Michael's completely
fantastic, wonderfully
defiant, mischievous response

37:45.733 --> 37:50.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to that, which wasn't the usual
contrite, yes, I have been
bad, I have a few personal

37:52.600 --> 37:56.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
issues -- it was to release
a pop song which proudly
celebrated sexuality and also...

37:57.633 --> 37:58.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM:
This was "Outside."

37:58.433 --> 37:59.367 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
TIM TEEMAN: Sorry.

37:59.367 --> 38:00.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This was "Outside," absolutely.

38:00.233 --> 38:02.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You're right, yes.

38:02.333 --> 38:06.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was a song that not only
proudly celebrated sexuality,
but also proudly and defiantly

38:08.467 --> 38:11.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
aimed itself squarely at law
enforcement, which famously
for years and years in your

38:11.433 --> 38:16.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
country and in Britain as well
would entrap gay men in public
lavatories just to arrest

38:17.967 --> 38:20.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
them, the use of
pretty policemen, we
called it in Britain.

38:20.100 --> 38:24.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in this video, George
skewers it all and also, if you
listen to the lyrics, celebrates

38:24.933 --> 38:29.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
defiantly his own
sexuality, which he spoke
about in later years.

38:30.800 --> 38:31.833 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He liked having public sex.

38:31.833 --> 38:33.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He spoke about it openly.

38:33.233 --> 38:34.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He had lovers.

38:34.333 --> 38:35.467 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He fell in love.

38:35.467 --> 38:36.467 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He had commitment issues.

38:36.467 --> 38:38.567 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He was horny.

38:38.567 --> 38:42.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He talked about all these things
in his song, and occasionally
in wonderful public interviews,

38:43.600 --> 38:45.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
which I talk about
in my article.

38:45.600 --> 38:49.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: You said that
the culture has changed quite
a bit since that notorious

38:50.200 --> 38:52.267 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
arrest.

38:52.267 --> 38:55.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do you think, if the next
George Michael is coming along
and knows his sexuality, that

38:55.000 --> 38:58.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
he could be more comfortable
today being who he is?

38:58.000 --> 39:00.267 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TIM TEEMAN: That's a very
interesting question.

39:00.267 --> 39:02.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I have been talking about
that with colleagues today.

39:02.733 --> 39:05.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I think we like to think
things have moved on.

39:05.533 --> 39:10.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think, for a certain level
of celebrity, I think things
have moved on, and I think

39:11.267 --> 39:13.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
careers are continuing.

39:13.300 --> 39:16.667 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You look at Neil Patrick Harris,
you look at Ellen, there are
some people who are excelling.

39:16.667 --> 39:20.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's wonderful, and it's
a demonstration of how far we
have come and how far we like

39:20.600 --> 39:22.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to think we have come.

39:22.533 --> 39:25.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then you look at the
top tier maybe of the music
industry and you look at the top

39:25.533 --> 39:30.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tier of Hollywood, and
there it remains, at
that very top tier, fear,
prejudice, a self-patrolling

39:34.367 --> 39:37.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
closet on the part
of celebrities and
their representation.

39:37.700 --> 39:42.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think we have yet to
really breach that sort of top,
top, A-list film star, music

39:43.500 --> 39:44.867 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
star moment.

39:44.867 --> 39:46.100 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's happening.

39:46.100 --> 39:47.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
There are more stars
out than ever before.

39:47.333 --> 39:49.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And we should be
happy about that.

39:49.900 --> 39:54.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I would hope, in the
future, that the example
of George Michael and the
openness and fierceness

39:56.267 --> 40:00.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and the defiance and the
mischief and the big smile and
the joy he took in some parts

40:02.333 --> 40:04.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of his life and what he tried
to convey to us in music and
how he spoke about it all

40:04.533 --> 40:09.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
in interviews, I hope
that younger stars and
even established stars
who haven't felt able

40:11.500 --> 40:13.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to come out will look at that
and think, he did it, and he
did it with such style, and

40:13.900 --> 40:16.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
such fierceness and with
such grace, let's do it.

40:16.233 --> 40:19.867 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All
right, Tim Teeman of The
Daily Beast, thanks for
this lovely remembrance.

40:19.867 --> 40:23.000 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
TIM TEEMAN: Thank you so much.

40:23.000 --> 40:28.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Now to
the "NewsHour" Bookshelf
for a novel about Israel
by its internationally

40:50.233 --> 40:52.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
renowned writer, Amos Oz.

40:52.333 --> 40:56.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He joined Jeffrey Brown at the
Center for Jewish History in
New York, in a conversation

40:56.233 --> 40:59.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
recorded before the recent U.N.
vote on Israeli settlements.

40:59.833 --> 41:04.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The 1950s, the
early years of the state of
Israel, a time of hope for

41:06.800 --> 41:11.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jews who'd seen a dream
come true, and fear about
what the future might bring.

41:11.100 --> 41:13.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
AMOS OZ, Author, "Judas": This
is the period of my own youth.

41:13.433 --> 41:17.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And these were, in terms
of Israeli history, the
years of the morning after.

41:17.867 --> 41:22.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So the country's
still young, but the question
is, what now or what next?

41:22.133 --> 41:27.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AMOS OZ: The question is what
now, but the question is also,
have we gone wrong somewhere?

41:28.267 --> 41:29.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Have we taken the
wrong turn someplace?

41:29.933 --> 41:34.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Amos Oz was
born in Jerusalem in 1939.

41:34.500 --> 41:39.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He spent many years living on a
kibbutz, served in the Israeli
army, and eventually became

41:40.367 --> 41:42.600 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
his country's best known writer.

41:42.600 --> 41:47.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
His new novel, "Judas," his
first in more than a decade,
is set in Jerusalem in those

41:47.533 --> 41:52.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
early years, the story of three
people at very different stages
in their lives and attitudes

41:53.467 --> 41:55.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
toward the new state.

41:55.833 --> 41:59.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AMOS OZ: I wanted to explore,
first and foremost, how
three totally different
human beings lived

42:01.767 --> 42:06.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for three months in the
same room, change and
almost reshape one another.

42:06.067 --> 42:11.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Do you start
with the notion of going back
to this period of what might

42:12.433 --> 42:13.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
come next, or do you
start with the characters?

42:13.233 --> 42:14.467 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How does it happen?

42:14.467 --> 42:15.767 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
AMOS OZ: Always
characters first.

42:15.767 --> 42:17.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Always?

42:17.800 --> 42:20.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AMOS OZ: And I walk around
pregnant with the characters
for a long time before I write

42:20.700 --> 42:22.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a single sentence.

42:22.733 --> 42:27.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And when, inside my head or
inside my guts, the characters
begin to do things to each

42:28.233 --> 42:30.967 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
other, what they do to
each other is the plot.

42:30.967 --> 42:32.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And then I can start writing.

42:32.900 --> 42:34.933 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What do we do to one another?

42:34.933 --> 42:39.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's the one and only subject of
literature, if you really have
to squeeze it in a nutshell.

42:39.433 --> 42:43.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Betrayal is
a key theme in this book, in
the ancient sense, through one

42:43.967 --> 42:48.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the character's studies of
the biblical story of Jesus and
Judas, and in modern Israel's

42:50.500 --> 42:51.700 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
founding.

42:51.700 --> 42:52.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: The
title is "Judas," right?

42:52.500 --> 42:54.533 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
AMOS OZ: Yes.

42:54.533 --> 42:56.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And this all
begins, I gather, out of an
interest of yours in the life of

42:56.733 --> 42:58.833 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Jesus.

42:58.833 --> 43:02.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AMOS OZ: Yes, but also out of
huge, growing resentment to
the ugly story about Judas,

43:05.500 --> 43:10.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about the 30 pieces of silver,
about the most notorious case in
history about the God killing.

43:12.567 --> 43:17.567 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In some point in the novel,
the protagonist, Shmuel Ash,
who is obsessed with his story,

43:18.667 --> 43:22.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
he writes about Judas
hanging himself.

43:22.033 --> 43:27.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Thus died the first
Christian and last Christian,
the only Christian.

43:28.067 --> 43:29.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's a very
provocative sentence.

43:29.400 --> 43:30.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It doesn't come from me.

43:30.533 --> 43:32.567 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It comes from the protagonist.

43:32.567 --> 43:36.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's trying to reconsider
the worst story ever told
by anyone in human history.

43:40.367 --> 43:45.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Amos Oz has been
a strong critic of Israel's
occupation of the West Bank and

43:47.433 --> 43:51.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
a longtime advocate for
a two-state solution
with the Palestinians.

43:51.900 --> 43:55.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's made him a traitor in the
eyes of some of his countrymen.

43:55.100 --> 43:59.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AMOS OZ: I wear these as a
badge of honor, because it
puts me in wonderful company.

43:59.933 --> 44:04.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Many, many great men and women
in history, prophets, statesmen,
intellectuals, artists,

44:07.500 --> 44:12.067 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
were accused of treason by many
of their own contemporaries.

44:12.067 --> 44:16.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What is the
job or role of a writer
in a country like Israel?

44:16.533 --> 44:21.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AMOS OZ: I resent the
very term role of writers
or role of literature.

44:22.600 --> 44:24.633 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I'm sorry.

44:24.633 --> 44:26.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think the right term should
be the gift of literature,
not the role of literature.

44:26.700 --> 44:27.867 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: The gift?

44:27.867 --> 44:30.000 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
AMOS OZ: Yes.

44:30.000 --> 44:34.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Makes us look one more time
at some things which we have
seen a million times, and we

44:37.300 --> 44:39.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
see them afresh.

44:39.333 --> 44:43.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Or, sometimes, it makes us
reconsider things that we were
sure we knew or we were sure

44:45.833 --> 44:47.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
we were convinced of.

44:47.400 --> 44:50.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: But
is it different in a
country such as Israel?

44:50.033 --> 44:52.667 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
AMOS OZ: I don't think so, no.

44:52.667 --> 44:54.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I don't think so.

44:54.733 --> 44:58.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think literature is based
on the deep human need to hear
stories and to tell stories.

45:02.500 --> 45:07.167 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It doesn't have to
serve any other purpose.

45:07.167 --> 45:12.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Oz's most famous
story may be his own, the
2004 autobiographical novel

45:14.200 --> 45:18.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
"A Tale of Love and Darkness,"
which has now been made into
a film by the actress Natalie

45:18.567 --> 45:20.600 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Portman.

45:20.600 --> 45:24.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a tragic family story of
a mother who commits suicide,
leaving behind her young

45:26.033 --> 45:29.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
son, and also a story of
a country in its early
years of statehood.

45:29.833 --> 45:34.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You have advocated a two-state
idea long before it was a
diplomatic solution, right?

45:36.467 --> 45:39.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Is that two-state solution dead?

45:39.900 --> 45:41.933 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
AMOS OZ: I don't think so.

45:41.933 --> 45:44.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I don't see any alternative
to the two-state solution.

45:44.600 --> 45:49.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is 50 years now
since I and a few of my
colleagues first advocated
the two-state solution.

45:52.200 --> 45:56.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Fifty years is a long time
in my life, but it's a
very short time in history.

45:56.800 --> 45:58.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Look, it's very simple.

45:58.400 --> 46:03.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There are two nations rightly
claiming the same tiny land.

46:04.600 --> 46:07.800 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They just don't trust the other.

46:07.800 --> 46:11.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There is a lack of courageous
leadership on both sides.

46:11.300 --> 46:16.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, it's like a patient
knowing that he has to undergo
a surgery, wanting to postpone

46:18.067 --> 46:19.667 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it because it's painful.

46:19.667 --> 46:21.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But the doctors are cowards.

46:21.333 --> 46:24.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
